Power Analysis

First, define the attributes and levels:

profiles <- cbc_profiles(
  price       = c(15, 20, 25), # Price ($1,000)
  fuelEconomy = c(20, 25, 30), # Fuel economy (mpg)
  accelTime   = c(6, 7, 8),    # 0-60 mph acceleration time (s)
  powertrain  = c('Gasoline', 'Electric')
)

Random design

Make a full-factorial (randomized) design:

design_rand <- cbc_design(
  profiles = profiles,
  n_resp   = 500, # Number of respondents
  n_alts   = 3,   # Number of alternatives per question
  n_q      = 6    # Number of questions per respondent
)

head(design_rand)
#>   profileID respID qID altID obsID price fuelEconomy accelTime powertrain
#> 1        12      1   1     1     1    25          20         7   Gasoline
#> 2        26      1   1     2     1    20          30         8   Gasoline
#> 3        49      1   1     3     1    15          25         8   Electric
#> 4        45      1   2     1     2    25          30         7   Electric
#> 5        33      1   2     2     2    25          25         6   Electric
#> 6        54      1   2     3     2    25          30         8   Electric

Simulate choices

data_rand <- cbc_choices(
    design = design_rand,
    obsID = "obsID"
)

Run power analysis

power_rand <- cbc_power(
    nbreaks = 10,
    data    = data_rand,
    pars    = c("price", "fuelEconomy", "accelTime", "powertrain"),
    outcome = "choice",
    obsID   = "obsID"
)

head(power_rand)

Here is a summary of the standard errors for each sample size:

ggplot(power_rand) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.05, color = "red", linetype = 2) +
  geom_point(aes(x = sampleSize, y = se, color = coef)) +
  expand_limits(y = 0) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 0.125)) +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(
    x = "Sample size", 
    y = "Standard error", 
    color = "Coefficient"
  )

D-efficient design

Make a D-efficient design:

priors <- list(
  price       = 0,
  fuelEconomy = 0,
  accelTime   = 0,
  powertrain  = 0
)

design_deff <- cbc_design(
  profiles  = profiles,
  n_resp    = 500, # Number of respondents
  n_alts    = 3, # Number of alternatives per question
  n_q       = 6, # Number of questions per respondent
  n_start   = 10, 
  n_blocks  = 1,
  priors = priors,
  method = "CEA"
)

head(design_deff)
#>   profileID respID qID altID obsID price fuelEconomy accelTime powertrain
#> 1        32      1   1     1     1    20          25         6   Electric
#> 2        23      1   1     2     1    20          25         8   Gasoline
#> 3        28      1   1     3     1    15          20         6   Electric
#> 4        31      1   2     1     2    15          25         6   Electric
#> 5        20      1   2     2     2    20          20         8   Gasoline
#> 6        36      1   2     3     2    25          30         6   Electric

Simulate choices

data_deff <- cbc_choices(
    design = design_deff,
    obsID  = "obsID",
    priors = priors
)

head(data_deff)
#>   profileID respID qID altID obsID price fuelEconomy accelTime powertrain

    nbreaks = 10,
